  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe produced vectorized IR differs
semantically from the source for the given test. Specifically, the target performs a sign
extension (sext) from a vector of i1 to a vector of i8 after freezing the i1 vector, while
the source semantics require a zero extension (zext) from i1 to i8. This changes true from
1 to -1 (0xFF), which then affects the unsigned comparison (ugt) and cascading
selects/subtractions, leading to the incorrect final reduction result.\n\n2. Analyzing
opt's Log:\n- The SLP pass recognized and vectorized a horizontal reduction and several
bundles. The key generated target sequence:\n  %6 = freeze <4 x i1> %3\n  %7 = sext <4 x
i1> %6 to <4 x i8>\n  %10 = icmp ugt <4 x i8> %7, %9\n- In the scalar source, the sequence
is: zext i1 -> i8, freeze i8, compare ugt. The target performs freeze on the i1 vector and
then casts to i8 during type reconciliation inside the ICmp vectorization path.\n- The
point where the cast choice is made is in vectorizeTree under the ICmp case (lines
~14840-14856): when L and R types differ, Builder.CreateIntCast is called with
GetOperandSignedness(Idx). If that returns true, it will sign-extend (sext); otherwise,
zero-extend (zext).\n- The log shows the erroneous sext, implying GetOperandSignedness
determined the operand as signed, even though i1 values used as boolean masks are
non-negative and should be extended as unsigned.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe lambda
GetOperandSignedness (around lines 14509-14519) determines signedness using MinBWs or by
checking if any scalar operand is not known non-negative via isKnownNonNegative. For i1
values, especially those feeding boolean casts/selects/comparisons, the correct behavior
is to treat them as unsigned (0 or 1), regardless of isKnownNonNegative proof. However,
the current heuristic can return true (signed) when non-negativity cannot be proven,
leading to sext from i1 to wider integer types. This is incorrect for boolean vectors in
comparisons/selects and results in semantic mismatches as demonstrated.\nTherefore, we
must special-case i1 types: if the operand entry corresponds to values of i1 (or vectors
of i1), signedness should be false (unsigned), guaranteeing zext when widening.\n\n4.
Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n-
Location: In BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree, within the lambda GetOperandSignedness defined around
lines 14509-14519.\n- Change: Add an early check to force unsigned for boolean types.
Pseudocode:\n  auto GetOperandSignedness = [&](unsigned Idx) {\n    const TreeEntry *OpE =
getOperandEntry(E, Idx);\n    // New: If all operand scalars are i1 (or the operand vector
element type is i1), treat as unsigned.\n    bool AllI1 = all_of(OpE->Scalars, [](Value
*R){\n      Type *Ty = R->getType();\n      return Ty->isIntegerTy(1) ||
(isa<VectorType>(Ty) && cast<VectorType>(Ty)->getElementType()->isIntegerTy(1));\n
});\n    if (AllI1)\n      return false;\n    bool IsSigned = false;\n    auto It =
MinBWs.find(OpE);\n    if (It != MinBWs.end())\n      IsSigned = It->second.second;\n
else\n      IsSigned = any_of(OpE->Scalars, [&](Value *R) {\n        return
!isKnownNonNegative(R, SimplifyQuery(*DL));\n      });\n    return IsSigned;\n  };\nThis
ensures widening casts on boolean predicates use zext, matching scalar semantics.\n\n5.
Conclusion:\nThe mismatch originates from choosing sign-extension when widening boolean
vectors to i8 within the ICmp vectorization path. By forcing unsigned widening for i1
operands in GetOperandSignedness, the vectorized IR will use zext instead of sext,
aligning with the scalar source behavior and fixing the Alive2 discrepancy. This change is
localized and consistent with LLVM's convention of treating booleans as 0/1 non-negative
values when casting to larger integer types.",
